{
  "text": "Coke or graphite was used as a reducing agent. The amount of reducing agent was increased from 0.7 up to 1.7 from the calculated stoichiometric molar value. Stoichiometric molar ratios of C/O higher than 1 were used to compensate the carbon consumed in reducing of reducible oxides such as MnO and SiO 2 . Figure 2 shows the effect of carbon stoichiometric molar ratio (C-S.R) on iron recovery. From the figure, the iron recovery increases as the amount of reductant increases up to about 1.5 of stoichiometric molar ratio. This result agrees with the result of Camci et al. [CITATION_1] . ",
